Calorie Estimation with Vision and Depth
A computer vision project that estimates the calorie content of plated meals using overhead RGB images and raw depth maps from the Nutrition5K dataset.

What it does
Built and compared multiple CNN architectures, evolving from a standard CNN to a final cross-modal attention model with residual blocks and an auxiliary depth head.
Fused RGB and depth data streams, using depth to guide spatial attention on the colour image.
Applied careful preprocessing (resizing to 128×96, normalisation, mirroring augmentation) and outlier handling.
Evaluated with 5-fold stratified cross-validation; final model achieved strong validation performance (MSE ≈ 4993).
Generated Kaggle submission predictions and performed detailed error analysis.

Practical multi-modal deep learning: combining RGB + depth for real-world scene understanding.
Modern CV techniques: residual connections, cross-modal fusion, and attention mechanisms.
End-to-end pipeline: data curation, augmentation, model design, evaluation, and deployment-ready CSV output.
Strong emphasis on practical performance, robustness, and iterative model improvement.

Technologies & Skills: PyTorch, torchvision, CNNs, Residual Networks, Cross-Modal Attention, Data Augmentation, Computer Vision, Multimodal Learning
